# General Embedded Development Rules

## Resource Optimization
- Minimize RAM/ROM usage
- Prefer static allocation over dynamic
- Use fixed-point math when possible, but floating-point is allowed in performance-sensitive tasks (ISR, ADC processing) if FPU is available
- Adjust floating-point usage frequency based on debugging feedback and target FPU presence
- Profile code size and execution time

## Interrupt Safety
- Keep ISRs short and deterministic
- Use volatile for shared variables
- Avoid floating-point in ISRs
- Prefer event flags over polling

## Peripheral Handling
- Initialize peripherals in correct order
- Use DMA for bulk data transfer
- Handle error conditions gracefully
- Document timing requirements

## Code Quality
- Use meaningful variable names
- Add Doxygen comments to APIs
- Avoid magic numbers
- Use assertions for debugging
- For ISR/DMA shared data, use `volatile` and name as `x_ready` / `x_flag`
- Note that `volatile` does not guarantee atomic access; use interrupt masking or atomic operations when needed

## Toolchain Considerations
- Be aware of compiler optimizations
- Use appropriate data types
- Handle endianness correctly
- Validate generated assembly when needed

## Testing Strategy
- Unit test utilities when possible
- Hardware validation mandatory
- Use oscilloscope/logic analyzer for timing
- Document test procedures